While the updates will begin on May 7, we can't give you a specific date or time when we will update your sites, as we expect the update process to take several weeks to complete. Updates will occur during the daily maintenance window (between 2 a.m. and 5 a.m. local time).

You still have time to do the update yourself

If you want to control when your site is updated, update your site's PHP version yourself before May 7.

We do not change any website content or update or change plugins, themes, or other code as part of the PHP version change; we only update the PHP version. Check your themes and plugins if your site experiences issues after we update the PHP version. PHP version incompatibilities are most likely to be found there.

In most cases, we cannot roll back an updated site to PHP 8.0. We recommend testing your sites and doing the update yourself to avoid any potential issues.

We're here to help

Everyone at Kinsta is dedicated to providing you with the fastest, safest, and most secure website hosting environment anywhere. We know that technology updates can be inconvenient and disruptive. But occasional updates are necessary to maintain the safety and performance you've come to expect.

We're here for you if you have questions about the PHP version changes, but we're limited in what we can do to fix errors related to the update.

  • We can check the error logs and advise which plugins or themes are causing fatal errors.
  • If you cannot reach the WordPress dashboard, we can help install plugin and theme updates (when possible) or disable or re-enable plugins.

If you need help with something outside the scope of our support, consider consulting the Kinsta Agency Directory to get in touch with one of our trusted agency clients.

We're here for you if you have questions about the PHP version changes. Feel free to connect with us in MyKinsta.
